Wejas wrote:
The Grand World Order wrote:It blew my mind when I used to encounter democratic countries with less oversight on government/military activities than the GWO despite the fact that, in the end, the Grand Commander still can wave her hand and tell potential auditors to proverbially fuck off


It's especially funny when said democratic nation loves to boast about how democratic and great their nation is, when their president casually creates a department that is basically the Stasi - but they attack "fascists and communists" rather than "counterrevolutionaries" or something stupid like that. Because clearly, a democratic president would be allowed to create a secret police without any oversight or even approval from congress.



To loresperg a bit, lore wise the Free States of America ended up founding an agency similar to a secret police, dubbed the "National Reconciliation Front" by the federal government in 2001. It's designated purpose was counter-terrorism and anti-insurgency operations post-2ACW, but it eventually morphed into an organization that imprisons anyone even suspected of supporting far-right or far-left militant organizations. This got approved narrowly by Congress and the Consul, with Congress in this timeline being a total of 624 seats, 472 in the HOR and 152 in the Senate, to a count of 312-309, 3 having abstained. It was dubbed the Reconciliation Commission of the Nation Act by Senator Erin Ryan, who is one of Leo Ryan's children, having taken inspiration from the Committee for Guyanese Stability, which was founded in 1979 after the Jonestown Massacre in this timeline resulted in the deaths of everyone in the camp. There was widespread public campaigns for and against the act, becoming a topic of concern that Gallup reported in a poll was prevalent in 67% of Americans, combining along with the South American Theatre of the 2ACW, which was a topic of concern for almost 8 in 10 Americans, for a total of 72.5, or roughly 73% of the population.

The Consul himself later stated in 2005, after it was revealed that members of the NRF had planned on staging a coup in the Cape Republic, had been acting as double agents for proclaimed terrorist organizations, refused to grant trial to detainees, arresting members of the local political opposition, in some cases even killing them, which was revealed in a report earlier that year, that "the NRF has become such a stain on our nation. It is an undemocratic construct, a de jure secret police, an army within a nation. It has betrayed the general population, it has shown that it cannot exist as a group, it cannot exist at all. It's intentions were necessary for temporary stability, yet that was the issue. We knew that it would eventually all go to hell, but we overlooked it for the short term. We needed the legitimacy, the stability, yet I'm afraid we've made a mistake. I have made a mistake.

If we allow this to still occur, we are not protecting the people as we should. We are not providing the suffice oversight to occur. We have failed as a government of the people, we have failed as a provisional authority. We are not a Nachtwächterstaat. We are a quasi-authoritarian regime in denial. We wish to be a democracy, yet we have created this stain. Accepting that fact will not fix anything immediately, but it will set us down a better path." It wasn't that the FSA proclaimed itself as a democracy, it proclaimed itself as a government of the people. It wasn't legitimate yet, hence the "provisional authority" shit. The issue was the fact that it failed it's intended purpose. Eventually the NRF got investigated by the federal government, and it's been heavily debated in Congress, and the Consul, whether to repeal the act and disband the organization as a whole.

Loresperg aside, I'm guilty of that to an extent, but significantly less now given my immediate mental revision of the NRF. I originally intended it as a combination of the CIA, Mossad, the NSA, OMON, and the FBI, but I've downsized it to a more domestic role. It'll eventually be overtaken by an org I haven't even thought of yet, but it's foreign counterpart will remain a secret for the moment.

More important cliche: wall of texts, and by that, I mean the ones where each paragraph is very long. I recently consumed a lot of Warhammer 4K wiki, and one thing that stood out is how often they space out their texts to give more emphasis on things. It is very rare for a paragraph there to exceed three sentences, and each sentence are also not that long. (I confess that my recent factbooks has been strongly influenced by their narrative style).

And now that I think about it, modern news articles are universally like this.

by The Grand World Order » Fri Feb 04, 2022 7:05 pm

Soviet Progonya wrote:Not gonna lie, I'm not too interested into making a super detailed form of government so realistic that it could actually exist. Governments can be really fucking confusing and I'm more interested in other areas of worldbuilding. Honestly, it might come down to me not being very knowledgeable when it comes to that specific area of politics. Ideologies are fairly easy to understand imo, but things like parliament or constitutions or devolution are complicated and to me kind of unintuitive to write.

Also mfw someone thinks you're a summerposter because you don't have 6730269836565 factbooks. I aint got infinite time and writer's block's a bitch.


Designing a government is a function of worldbuilding. These structures themselves provide a setting through which other stories take place. Granted, in a regular novel, this would be done through showing readers via events, character actions/reactions, etc rather than a purely expository writing (factbooks,) but the reality is that we do not have a linear, connected story on NS; the options are either a massive factbook that handles all the exposition, or putting the exposition in each thread we take part in. A lot of people put insane amounts of detail into their factbooks so they won't have to spend time explaining it elsewhere- but also, because RP on NS has mostly died, so there's not really anywhere else to show their concept.

Also, worldbuilding on a larger scale is difficult, because you share a world with so many different users' countries, to the point where realistically speaking, the planet would be so hyperdense that life as we know it would not be possible. For instance, the GWO is the United Nations after two world wars level much of the current world, and the Western fash-populists we hear so much about seize the initiative and throw a coup right after the UN restores order for the most part. This gets confusing when there's a ton of alternate Americas out there, and the scope of global affairs far exceeds that of the former RL world.
